    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nIt's not possible to have the Nvim server exit automatically when a client attached to a non-stdio channel crashes or is killed. This leads to a dangling server, which may be undesired in cases like after `:restart` on a server that was previously embedded. As can be seen in the `:restart` tests, after `:restart` killing the TUI won't stop the restarted server, so the server needs to be quit manually.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nA client on non-stdio channel can become an \"owner\" of an Nvim server, so that the server exits automatically when the channels is closed.\n\nA possible solution is to add an \"owner\" flag to `nvim_ui_attach`. However:\n- It's not clear how the server should be behave when multiple UI set the \"owner\" flag.\n- This doesn't allow a non-UI client to become an \"owner\".",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Good idea!\n\n> not clear how the server should be behave when multiple UI set the \"owner\" flag\n\nInstead of one owner, there could be a list of owners. The server keeps running until all owners disconnect? (Maybe \"owner\" isn't the most intuitive term.)\n\n> add an \"owner\" flag to `nvim_ui_attach`\n\nCould do that, but we also want a more generic way to set \"channel properties\". We could either cram that into `nvim_set_client_info` (but need to expose that for \"non-remote\" Lua), or introduce something like `nvim_chan_set(chan:integer, opts:dict)`. This will also eliminate `nvim__chan_set_detach`.",
            "created_at": "2026-04-13T23:15:28Z",
